    ('60', 'Applications: Dockerize Cloud Platform Applications', 'Dockerize each of the Cloud Node.js applications as well as any services owned by Cloud (i.e. memcached, NGINX, etc).There are multiple benefits to doing this. In the short-term, there are the following benefits to the development and quality assurance process:# *Speed-of-development:* Developers will have quick access to the platform as a whole and can test integration issues and submit cross-team pull requests quickly and efficiently. # *Quality assurance benefits:* QA and product can run the entire platform with one command on their own machines. Infrastructure issues within the Cloud Platform will not affect productivity. # *Less environment-related bugs & surprises during releases:* Developers can debug upper environments, because they can run the deployed environments on their own machines. In the long-term, dockerizing the platform will directly prepare us for greater scalability and robustness.# *Ability to scale any service horizontally in the public cloud* #* **Implementing Docker means we can directly move to AWS, if needed. Otherwise, we can easily scale on-prem through Kubernetes or Docker Swarm if that''s the decision that''s made. # *Ability to update base image software (like Node):* #* **Previously, this required a entirely new infrastructure build-out which can take up to six months. With Docker, base images can be updated with one line of code, and testing that would take ~ 1-2 weeks. *Acceptance Criteria:*# NGINX, memcached, and the Node.js must live in separate Docker containers. The following base images should be used for each service: ** *PM2:* *** *keymetrics/pm2:latest-alpine* *** *Why?:* You could call Node.js directly as the Docker entry, but you would lose capabilities like performant built-in clustering (leverage more than one CPU), correct PID 1 signal handling/forwarding, application configuration, fast application re-spawn on crash and so on. Given PM2 provides a more robust production environment, we should leverage PM2''s official/maintained docker image. Alpine is chosen as a base image due to greatly decreasing the docker image size. ** *NGINX:* *** *nginx:mainline-alpine-perl* *** *Why?:* NGINX has its own, official/maintained, image that we should leverage. Perl is chosen because it provides a means to pass down environment variables into nginx configurations, if desired. (This is not trivial, but possible with the perl module). Alpine is chosen as a base image due to greatly decreasing the docker image size.  ** *memcached:* *** *memcached:1.5-alpine* *** *Why?:* Latest, stable official/maintained memcached image.  # Containers should follow the principle of least privilege. ** i.e. PM2 should run as the `pm2` user, NGINX as `nginx`, etc. Those users should be set up with no privileges other than those they explicitly need. # All environment behavior should pivot off of the NODE_ENV variable passed to the container. Config should be simplified, in one spot, and not repeated. # Image entry commands should call ', 244, 5, 2, null, '2019-05-30T00:00:00', '2019-07-10T00:00:00', null, 'Cloud - Jun-Jul 2019', '2019-05-30T00:00:00', '2019-07-10T00:00:00', 0, 0, '13', 'Cloud on Public Cloud (AWS)', 'CLP-873'),
