    ('161', 'AC sorting code refactoring', 'Move sorting logic from servlet to solr plugin.specification updated on: https://mswiki.morningstar.com/display/PDS/Sorting+Algorithmsummary:Priority of work(plan accordingly based on capacity and release time constrain):Remove the nondeterministic (most important one)Add option to use field priority over security type priorityUse length of OS01W asc(name match) or length of OS001 asc (ticker match) as tiebreaker (exploratory)', -1, 5, 5, null, null, null, null, 'PI0', '2019-05-01T00:00:00', '2019-05-31T00:00:00', 11, 11, null, null, 'SRCH-677'),
    ('162', 'Add Varnish Cache to AC/IDS', 'Add Varnish Cache to AC/IDS to improve performance and capacity for Phoenix/Quicktake''s to use ID service/Autcomplete.----------From: Dan Collins Sent: Friday, February 13, 2015 9:59 AMTo: Hangfei Cheng; Yikui Jiao; Ramanathan KrishnanCc: Esther Brookfield; Robert YuSubject: Re: id service capacityWe鈥檝e previously looked at introducing varnish when load increased as a solution for capacity. However, keeping it out of the picture so far has reduced some complexity (coordination with refresh times, one-off consistency issues, etc). If we鈥檙e seeing a traffic change, I think it鈥檇 be worth revisiting Varnish and adding it to the stack. This said, we鈥檇 need to do a few things to get this set up:A. Create a request to Core Services Team that includes:1.	Updated architecture with Varnish in the stack2.	Expected requests (which we should have from the awesome work you guys have already done in testing)3.	All other requirements here: https://mswiki.morningstar.com/display/CORE/Project+RequirementsB. Create an initial VCL and consider cache invalidation as part of the solution:1.	Propose a caching strategy that aligns with our data refresh for both autocomplete and id service. 2.	Once the work is accepted from A, we can work with Fred / Steve to propose a cache invalidation strategy. As of Varnish 3.0, we can introduce a specific HTTP request for this type of work to be implemented in VCL. Unlike Akamai, if we don鈥檛 provide this, there is no way for us to flush cache without manually intervening. Cache invalidation strategies here in the Varnish manual help: https://www.varnish-software.com/static/book/Cache_invalidation.html Examples of existing VCL鈥檚 live here: https://msstash.morningstar.com/projects/CORESVC/repos/varnish/browse.3.	Ensure both ID Service and Autocomplete endpoints properly respond with appropriate caching headers.C. Reference1.	Prior work in this same vein would include Autocomplete for Microsoft, which uses Akamai externally to cache. We can consider issues we鈥檝e seen with Akamai (invalidation, load spikes, etc) as input for the work we do setting up varnish.)Additionally, introducing varnish into the stack is an architectural change, so we鈥檒l need to notify the CAB of the change. We should have all of the above completed in staging first to show the result and have adequate information to defend the approach. We may still have to consider individual server capacity based on data set size or other functionality we may add, but varnish is a beast and if we can do our caching properly, we鈥檒l be able to save a lot of load on our stack. Thanks! -Dan--------------', -1, 5, 5, null, null, null, null, 'PI0', '2019-05-01T00:00:00', '2019-05-31T00:00:00', 2, 2, null, null, 'SRCH-675'),
