    ('1046', 'CIT/SMA/Model Divorce', '+Background+:聽鈥燭he separate account universe was created first, built with the best degree of knowledge at the time. As our data coverage expanded, other vehicles such as collective investment trusts and models were added to the separate account database. With鈥痳enewed focus on emerging managed investment vehicles, our team has evaluated the data structure for these opaque investment types.聽In order for聽enhancements to be made that accommodate the needs of these individual universes, we have introduced two new legal structures and will be migrating these investments.+Technical Details+:聽 * +New CIT Universe+:聽collective investment trusts, currently housed in the separate account legal structure 20, under account type 2 will migrate to legal structure 43. This will only impact US domiciled investments.聽聽 聽 聽 聽 聽 聽If you鈥檙e looking for a test security in this new legal structure, you can use the following:聽F0000112N6聽鈥?* +New Model Universe+: models, currently housed in the separate account legal structure 20, will migrate to legal structure 55. Lia will provide a comprehensive list of impacted investments in a subsequent notification. This will impact US and Australian domiciled investments.聽聽 聽 聽 聽 聽聽If you鈥檙e looking for a test security in this new legal structure, you can use the following:聽F0000118K5聽*Data and Research Recommendations*聽We would recommend the CIT and model universes be broken out from both a feeds and software display perspective. These new legal structures give us flexibility to improve each universe as is appropriate for the investment type. We expect that as other projects come along, there will be differences in the data points that are applicable to each universe.聽', -1, 5, 5, '#ff4e4d', null, null, null, null, null, null, 3, 3, null, null, 'DSSV-8509'),
    ('1047', 'EC entitlement in AMS', 'Break Down from Sunny Xia聽|*Task*|*Estimation (workday)*||Handle EC and DataFeed user聽 in AMS|3||Handle EC and DataFeed user permission in AMS|5||Handle EC and DataFeed admin in AMS|2||Update Direct Api|1||Database support|10||Enhance Content Catalog to support EC/DataFeed User|3||EC/DataFeed user login|3| # Morningstar Direct user manages the EC users. We will set up Direct account for Morningstar EC employee and assign admin rights to him/her. He/she logons AMS as Direct EC admin user and manage EC users/entitlement. By this way, we don鈥檛 need to change our login process. # EC admin user will see two tabs 鈥?User and Entitlement. Under tab User, EC admin can create/update/delete/search EC users. Under tab Entitlement, EC admin can search users and entitle them. # EC admin will only see/search EC users # EC users only exists in AMS. They will not be sync up to any other system, say UIM etc. # EC user鈥檚 permissions will be isolated from other products # DirectApi will accept EC product code to retrieve EC user鈥檚 permissionsWe will still need index providers to authorize the use of their data, so we want the EC client requests to be sent to the index provider to approve or deny. But we want the request to be clearly marked as Enterprise Components so that the provider understands that the request is not from a Direct user.聽We are OK with an EC admin user being the one to submit the requests on behalf of the client, but would prefer to expose an interface to the EC client so that they can submit the request themselves and we are removed from the process. Maybe this would be a separate project. I am not very familiar with the UI in Direct where the user submits their requests. Is it possible to access this interface directly through a browser? Or is it available only through Direct? If it can be accessed independently, we could share the EC client service account credentials with the client, and they could enter their own requests.