    ('2361', 'IIMOB Extract Mobile Service shared modules to libraries', 'Value PropositionCore elements of the Mobile Service application, when hosted in shared libraries, can be leveraged between product-specific services. These shared libraries will reduce fully duplicated code between the product-specific services and both applications will benefit from changes and improvements to the shared, library.Assumptions & PrerequisitesMobile Service is based on the Play Framework and, as such, many aspects of the application leverage various parts of the framework. There may be opportunities to simplify/remove dependencies on Play in the libraries, though it isn''t an essential requirement. For example, we could leverage TypeSafe''s configuration library directly rather than indirect access through Play.Some amount of this work must be completed before the "split" can begin.Libraries will be based upon standalone, versioned projects which use dependency management, are built by and deployed through Jenkins, and are deployed to NEXUS.Libraries will adhere to semantic versioning.Pull request from both the teams will be reviewed by all.Separate repository for a shared library and both the team has access to it.High-Level TaskingFigure out what to do with RequestContextUse of the RequestContext class is prevalent across many layers of the application. If we can figure out a way to refactor away from it or provide a more appropriate abstraction depending on common use cases, then this class will not need to show up in other libraries. MOBSERV-534 - Introduce logging-specific abstraction to be used with ReqeustConext OPEN describes one, possible approach.RequestContext has a reference to the Customer object. We should determine whether or not this relationship is necessary and/or whether some different relationship may be created. For example, the module/library containing the RequestContext could export a CustomerInfo interface to which the Customer class would adhere.Caching packageEstablish a clearer APIClasses like service.caching.GemFireCacheManager do not belong in the library as it''s makeup is application-specific.Refactoring to certain extentDependency initialization (entry point to module)Config of caching propertiesWeb Service PackageEndpoint communication extraction, serialization and transformationWhat are the dependencies of specific packages?Async/Tasks/JobsAnalyze whether there is any benefit to putting these in a library. Superclasses might be a good option, but specific, concrete jobs may not as they depend on model objects which we likely will not want to include in shared libraries.Service/Repository ConsiderationsAnalyze whether there is any benefit to putting these in a library. Some common service/repository combinations may be worthwhile in cases such as Securities (Info/Detail/Quote) though model classes would also have to be moved to the libraries.Controllers And Filters (Actions)We have some controllers that are specific to products (such as Retail / Advisor ) and some controllers that are shared by all b', -1, 0, 5, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 0, 0, null, null, 'IIMOB-1198'),
